line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">The issue is certainly <em>not</em> any lack of talent among the =
filmmakers working
with Warners. Quite the opposite: The studio has sought relationships with =
the best names in the business. Promising a full theatrical release, Warner=
s snatched <strong>Margot Robbie</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>Wuthering Heights</=
em> from Netflix with an offer of $80 million=E2=80=94much less than the $1=
50 million dangled by the streamer. The success of <em>Wonka</em> and <em>D=
une</em> led to a first-look arrangement with <strong>Timoth=C3=A9e Chalame=
t</strong>. And De Luca and Abdy got a meeting with <strong>Tom Cruise
</strong>following a call they had made to his agent, CAA=E2=80=99s <strong=
>Maha Dakhil</strong>, asking her to pass along their thanks to Cruise for =
working to save theaters during the pandemic. With Zaslav joining that meet=
ing, Warners came away with a nonexclusive first-look deal. (Paramount, whi=
ch had long been Cruise=E2=80=99s primary residence, was not looped in on t=
he discussions.) Of course, Cruise doesn=E2=80=99t work cheap, and he=E2=80=
=99s now shooting a big-budget <strong>Alejandro G. I=C3=B1=C3=A1rritu</str=
ong> film that
has fallen behind schedule in part due to a <strong>John Goodman</strong> h=
ip injury.<br/><br/>That film isn=E2=80=99t due until 2026, but the remaind=
er of this year will bring a string of films with the generous budgets and =
deal terms that have Hollywood veterans shuddering. Consider the <strong>Mi=
chael B. Jordan</strong>=E2=80=93starring <em>Sinners</em>, a period vampir=
e movie from <strong>Ryan Coogler</strong>, the gifted director of <em>Cree=
d</em> and the <em>Black Panther</em> movies. Sources say that
Universal and Sony, among others, were very interested in making <em>Sinner=
s,</em> but dropped out when Coogler=E2=80=99s team asked not only for firs=
t-dollar gross and final cut, but also for ownership of the film 25 years a=
fter release. That request was an absolute deal-breaker for both studios.<b=
r/><br/>Sources with knowledge of the situation said that Warners=E2=80=99 =
seasoned president of business affairs, <strong>Steve Spira</strong>, objec=
ted strenuously to that highly unusual request, but was overruled.
The arrangement even prompted chatter among the company=E2=80=99s board mem=
bers. To some in Hollywood, this was another example of malpractice. =E2=80=
=9CIf you=E2=80=99re Mike, your job is supposed to be improving the library=
,=E2=80=9D said a top exec at another company. =E2=80=9CWhen you make movie=
s and don=E2=80=99t own rights, you=E2=80=99re not doing that.=E2=80=9D<br/=
><br/><em>Sinners</em>, set for release April 18, also went well over budge=
t, though insiders said that, contrary to rumors, Coogler is covering overa=
ges out of his fees and backend. And
unlike Bong, Coogler has been receptive to feedback from test screenings. B=
ut bottom line, said a source, the film would need to open at around $50 mi=
llion to $60 million to have a hope of reaching breakeven, which feels like=
 a tough bar to meet.<br/><br/>De Luca and Abdy can=E2=80=99t be blamed for=
 the upcoming <em>Alto Knights</em>, in which <strong>Robert De Niro</stron=
g> plays two characters. That one was Zaslav=E2=80=99s baby, an early-days =
decision that he made after running into his friend, the writer
<strong>Nick</strong> <strong>Pileggi</strong>. That certainly surprised th=
e town, but maybe not as much as De Luca and Abdy=E2=80=99s decision to gre=
enlight Anderson=E2=80=99s next film, tentatively titled <em>One Battle Aft=
er Another</em>, with a budget widely believed to be at least $150 million.=
 (Warners disputes that number.) The film features bona fide movie star <st=
rong>Leo DiCaprio</strong>, and Warners=E2=80=99 logic is that Leo is a maj=
or difference-maker. DiCaprio hasn=E2=80=99t faltered at the box office muc=
h,
though he is mortal, with disappointing numbers from such films as the <str=
ong>Clint Eastwood</strong> drama<strong> </strong><em>J. Edgar</em>, in 20=
11, and <strong>Martin Scorsese</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>Killers of the Flowe=
r Moon</em>, in 2023. The world will soon know whether he can propel this p=
roject to a multiple of Anderson=E2=80=99s previous box office best.<br/><b=
r/>Longtime industry insiders are also scratching their heads at <strong>Ma=
ggie Gyllenhaal</strong>=E2=80=99s Frankenstein riff, <em>The
Bride</em>, starring <strong>Christian Bale</strong> and <strong>Jessie Buc=
kley</strong>. Gyllenhaal has directed only one film: artsy Netflix project=
 <em>The Lost Daughter</em>, which earned three Oscar nominations. From tha=
t movie to a budget of more than $100 million is quite an astonishing leap.=
 =E2=80=9CTo give her anything more than $15 million to make the movie is i=
rresponsible, as far as I=E2=80=99m concerned,=E2=80=9D said the head of on=
e production company. The film, which was shot in New York, is said to
have had worrisome test screenings that suggest it may be too arthouse and =
not squarely enough in the horror genre to generate the big audience that t=
he budget demands. Abdy is now tasked with getting it into shape for a plan=
ned release in the fall, and word is she=E2=80=99s having a hard time of it=
=2E (Warners declined to comment.)</p></div>
