argin:0;">In early January, as all this ferment was bubbling up, De Luca an=
d Abdy summoned
Warners=E2=80=99 marketing chief, <strong>Josh Goldstine</strong>, into the=
ir office and sacked him, even though he had signed a three-year deal just =
a year earlier. They also jettisoned <strong>Andrew Cripps</strong>, their =
head of international distribution, who was quickly snapped up by Disney. W=
arners had recently disappointed in its overseas releases of <em>Twisters</=
em> and <em>Beetlejuice Beetlejuice</em>, but the Goldstine move mystified =
many people, who credit him with getting <em>Dune: Part
One</em> to a $411 million gross while the pandemic weighed on audiences, a=
nd the sequel to $715 million in 2024=E2=80=94and, above all, for selling W=
arners=E2=80=99 biggest movie ever, <em>Barbie</em>, as brilliantly as it c=
ould have been sold.<br/><br/>Everyone in Hollywood knows that when things =
go wrong at a studio, marketing is the first to get blamed. But why fire Go=
ldstine now, before this string of risky movies rolls into theaters? Inside=
rs said De Luca and Abdy cited frustration at what they saw as his
one-size-fits-all approach=E2=80=A6 yet Goldstine=E2=80=99s team remains, a=
nd he is not being replaced. It also appears that Warners, consistent with =
other divisions of Warner Bros. Discovery in the Zaslav era, is trying to s=
pend less on marketing, which seems particularly risky with original films =
that aren=E2=80=99t presold. (For his part, Goldstine is currently consider=
ing options that include becoming a marketing consultant on <strong>Greta G=
erwig</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>Narnia</em> movies at Netflix.)<br/><br/>With =
all this
as a backdrop, rumors flew late last week that De Luca and Abdy were out. A=
sked for comment, Zaslav=E2=80=99s spokesman, <strong>Robert Gibbs</strong>=
, responded, =E2=80=9CThere is no truth to that rumor.=E2=80=9D And that wa=
s it. Needless to say, the statement likely will do little to stop the rumo=
r mill from grinding on. Zaslav has been said to be leaning toward replacin=
g them with <strong>Peter Safran</strong>, the co-chair and co-C.E.O. (with=
 <strong>James Gunn</strong>) of DC Studios. But simultaneously, there are
rumors that Zaslav will initiate a search for new leadership.<br/><br/>Mean=
while, Gunn and Safran are busy with a little project of their own: <em>Sup=
erman</em>=E2=80=94the July release that has now taken on almost incalculab=
le importance to Warner Bros. Discovery. If Warners can=E2=80=99t finally m=
ake the DC franchise work, there is genuine fear that the studio will go th=
e way of Fox, which was swallowed by Disney in 2019.<br/><br/>Warners was o=
nce considered the Tiffany of movie studios. Sure, the corporate jets
and the nice Acapulco retreat are long gone, but Warner Bros. is still fund=
amental to the industry=E2=80=99s image of itself. Presiding over the destr=
uction of the place is hardly the Hollywood ending that Zaslav envisioned. =
=E2=80=9CAn essential element of the stock price is believing that the I.P.=
 of DC is meaningful,=E2=80=9D said one Warners veteran. =E2=80=9CDavid bet=
 big that they can show the world that the DC I.P. can have real value. <em=
>Superman</em> is the first movie. That will set the tone. They have a trem=
endous
amount riding on it.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a staggering amount of pressur=
e on Safran and especially Gunn, who is directing. But if the movie doesn=
=E2=80=99t work, at least no one can say it=E2=80=99s Mike and Pam=E2=80=99=
s fault. Unless folks want to blame the marketing=E2=80=A6</p></div>
